C. XV1. “ DE VAS& ETC„ PICTIS.”

For painting earthenware vessels the Greeks were accustomed to use coloured fluxes mixed with different pigments suitable to the purpose. This art would naturally lead to that of painting upon glass, the transition would likewise be immediate. In chap. xv. Theophilus informs us that the same people made “ glass tablets, as in window work,'’ which they ornamented with gold, laying a flux behind the leaf in order to protect it. This was principally used in mosaic work: the decoration of vases with gold leaf and coloured ornamental work, having been applied to glass, as well as fictile vases and cups, became transferred to the glass plates‚ and thus were introduced into window-work.

Eraclius, who is quoted by Theophilus in the third book, gives a chapter upon this subject.
